<p>
<seg id=1> At the same time, in Chinatown, Jakarta, the capital of Indonesia, Chinese people and the native Indonesians fought together to protect their homes. </seg>
<seg id=2> After the serious riots in May, Chinatown was again the target of violent activities. </seg>
<seg id=3> Here is another report from Jakarta by VOA reporter Gland. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Night had fallen. The soldiers fired a warning shot to disperse the young men in Chinatown who were throwing stones at the soldiers. </seg>
<seg id=5> A couple of hours ago, hundreds of people burnt a bank that was less than 1km away from the Presidential Palace, and the flames spread quickly to the shops nearby. </seg>
<seg id=6> These young men forced open the doors of the shops with a light pole. </seg>
<seg id=7> When the Chinese were attacked on Saturday, one of them was pulled into the street and beaten by a group of people, then he was thrown into a ditch. </seg>
<seg id=8> Later, the soldiers drove an armed truck there and they saved the severely wounded person. </seg>
<seg id=9> There were tanks on patrol duty in the street with stones and broken glass. Hundreds of soldiers wore guns and tear bombs, protecting the local commercial areas from the rioters. </seg>
<seg id=10> The businessmen who dealt in electrical products moved their shop after the riots in May. </seg>
<seg id=11> The reporter saw a 29 year-old man named Min wearing shorts and belt, on guard behind the roadblock made of wire netting. </seg>
<seg id=12> The young man who was working in a computer company said that he and his Islamic neighbors would be on guard there the whole night to protect their homes from the rioters. </seg>
<seg id=13> Mr. Min said that his neighbors made the wire netting after the serious riots in May, but they didn't think it would be used so soon. </seg>
<seg id=14> The citizens dispersed a lot of strangers with big sticks when they built the roadblock. </seg>
<seg id=15> A citizen named Daciat wore a Moslem hat and sarong. </seg>
<seg id=16> He told the reporter that most of the young men came to Chinatown from other places after they heard news of the riots. </seg>
<seg id=17> The rioters destroyed a railway station near the road. When the soldiers dispersed them, they threw shoes, computers and clothes hangers everywhere. </seg>
</p>
